 Villain Nor Victim attempts to correct these polarizing perspectives by presenting a critical feminist analysis of the drug world. By shifting the discussion to one centered on women's agency and empowerment, this book reveals the complex experiences and social relationships of women addicts. Essays explore a range of topics, including the many ways that women negotiate the illicit drug world, how former drug addicts manage the more intimate aspects of their lives as they try to achieve abstinence, how women tend to use intervention resources more positively than their male counterparts, and how society can improve its response to female substance abusers by moving away from social controls (such as the criminalization of prostitution) and rehabilitative programs that have been shown to fail women in the long term. Advancing important new perspectives about the position of women in the drug world, this book is essential reading in courses on women and crime, feminist theory, and criminal justice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aDrug abusexPrevention. 0aDrug abusexTreatment. 0aFemale offendersxDrug use. 0aFemale offendersxRehabilitation. 0aWomen drug addicts. 0aWomen prisonersxDrug use. 0aWomen prisonersxRehabilitation. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAnderson, Tammy1 aAnderson, Tammy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBaskin, Deborah1 aBerger, Michele Tracy1 aBlankenship, Kim1 aCoontz, Phyllis1 aEttore, Elizabeth1 aGray, Alison1 aGreibel, Cate1 aHartwell, Stephanie1 aKatsulis, Yasmina1 aKelley, Margaret1 aMalloch, Margaret1 aMullins, Christopher1 aSaum, Christine1 aSommers, Ira1 aTracy, Carol08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gr